05225nam a22007815i 9780674283855DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20131989mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013935850  a97806742838557 a10.4159/harvard.97806742838552doi  a(DE-B1597)247254  a(OCoLC)900819222  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aB2948b.F67 1989eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a149/.73/092191 aForster, Michael N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHegel and Skepticism /cMichael N. Forster.  aReprint 2013 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©1989  a1 online resource (256 p.) :billsutrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. HEGEL ON THE HISTORY OF SKEPTICISM -- tONE. The Superiority of Ancient to Modern Skeptidsm -- tTWO. The Limitations of Ancient Skepticism -- tPART II. SKEPTICAL CULTURE IN HEGEL'S PHILOSOPHY OF HISTORY -- tTHREE. The Theory of a Historical Ur-teilung -- tFOUR. The Collapse of Greek Ethical Life -- tFIVE. The Alienated Realms of Culture and Faith -- tPART III. THE EPISTEMOLOGICAL DEFENSE OF HEGEL'S SYSTEM -- tSIX. Hegel's Epistemology? -- tSEVEN. Two Defenses against Skepticism -- tEIGHT. Further Defenses against Skepticism -- tNINE. The Proof for Nonbelievers -- tTEN. The Dialectical Method in Hegels Epistemology -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rejection by Anglo-Saxon philosophers of much "continental philosophy" (from Hegel on down) is largely based on the perceived failure of continental thinkers to grapple with the tough questions of epistemology in general and skepticism in particular. Forster demonstrates that Hegel did not in fact ignore epistemology, but on the contrary he fought a tireless and subtle campaign to defeat the threat of skepticism. Forster's work should dispel once and for all the view that Hegel was naive or careless in epistemological matters. Forster begins by discussing Hegel's critical interpretation of the skeptical tradition, in particular his convincingly argued case for the superiority of ancient over modern skepticism. He goes on to show that the difficulties characteristic of ancient skepticism play a crucial and fascinating role in Hegel's philosophy of history. Hegel sees in the emergence of these difficulties an explanation of why the harmonious unified Greek culture collapsed and was replaced by the division and alienation characteristic of subsequent western culture. Finally, Forster examines the elaborate and ingenious system of defenses erected by Hegel to protect his philosophical thought against skeptical difficulties, as the core of a somewhat broader epistemological project. Along the way, Forster makes much that has hither to remained obscure in Hegel's texts intelligible for the first time. This book should cause a re-evaluation of Hegel, and German Idealism generally, and contribute to a re-evaluation of the skeptical tradition in philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPhilosophie. 0aSkepticismxHistoryy19th century. 0aSkepticism. 4aHegel, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich, 1770-1831 -- Views on skepticism. 4aSkepticism -- History -- 19th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Philosophy eBook Packagez9783110353525oZDB-23-HPI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067428384840uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067428